281	## Phase 2: POST-to-loopback — keep the JWT out of the browser URL
282	
283	### Overview
284	
285	Replace the current GET `?token=…` redirect handoff with a POST that carries the JWT in the request body. The loopback server validates the `Origin` header, parses `{ token, state }` from JSON, and settles. The web bridge renders its own "Signed in — close this tab" UI after the POST resolves.
286	
287	### Changes Required
288	
289	#### 1. `apps/desktop/src/main/auth-flow.ts` — POST-only loopback
290	
291	**Replace the single `request` handler with method-aware branching plus CORS preflight.**
292	
293	```ts
294	// Reuse the existing getApiOrigin() helper at auth-flow.ts:10-17 — don't
295	// duplicate. index.ts:45-52 has the same helper (getApiOriginForCsp); a
296	// future cleanup can consolidate into apps/desktop/src/shared/ but that's
297	// out of scope for this plan.
298	const ALLOWED_ORIGIN = getApiOrigin();
299	
300	function applyCors(res: ServerResponse): void {
301	  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Origin", ALLOWED_ORIGIN);
302	  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Methods", "POST, OPTIONS");
303	  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Headers", "content-type");
304	  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Max-Age", "600");
305	  res.setHeader("Vary", "Origin");
306	  // Chrome Private Network Access: public origins (https://lightfast.ai)
307	  // fetching loopback targets require this explicit opt-in or the browser
308	  // blocks the request. Dev (http://localhost:3024 → 127.0.0.1) is
309	  // loopback→loopback and unaffected; prod is public→loopback and would
310	  // silently break without this header.
311	  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Private-Network", "true");
312	}
313	
314	async function readJsonBody(req: IncomingMessage): Promise<unknown> {
315	  const chunks: Buffer[] = [];
316	  let total = 0;
317	  const MAX = 16 * 1024; // JWT payloads are well under 16KB; reject anything larger
318	  for await (const chunk of req) {
319	    const buf = Buffer.isBuffer(chunk) ? chunk : Buffer.from(chunk);
320	    total += buf.length;
321	    if (total > MAX) {
322	      // Tear down the socket so a malicious client can't keep streaming
323	      // bytes we've already committed to rejecting. Without this, the TCP
324	      // connection remains open until the client closes it — a trivial
325	      // local-port-hold vector.
326	      req.destroy();
327	      throw new Error("payload too large");
328	    }
329	    chunks.push(buf);
330	  }
331	  return JSON.parse(Buffer.concat(chunks).toString("utf8")) as unknown;
332	}
333	
334	server.on("request", async (req, res) => {
335	  try {
336	    const origin = req.headers.origin ?? "";
337	    // Reject empty Origin too — legitimate browser requests always set it on
338	    // cross-origin fetches, and local non-browser clients have no business
339	    // hitting this loopback (the desktop is the only intended client, and it
340	    // doesn't go through this path).
341	    //
342	    // Note: the 403 response intentionally omits CORS headers. The browser
343	    // reports this as an opaque CORS failure rather than leaking which
344	    // origins are allowed — deliberate defense-in-depth, not a bug. If a
345	    // future debugger sees "CORS error" in DevTools for a malicious origin,
346	    // that's the expected behavior.
347	    if (origin !== ALLOWED_ORIGIN) {
348	      res.writeHead(403, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
349	      res.end("Forbidden origin");
350	      return;
351	    }
352	    const url = new URL(req.url ?? "/", `http://${LOOPBACK_HOST}:${port}`);
353	    if (url.pathname !== CALLBACK_PATH) {
354	      res.writeHead(404, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
355	      res.end("Not Found");
356	      return;
357	    }
358	    if (req.method === "OPTIONS") {
359	      applyCors(res);
360	      res.writeHead(204);
361	      res.end();
362	      return;
363	    }
364	    if (req.method !== "POST") {
365	      res.writeHead(405, { "Content-Type": "text/plain", Allow: "POST" });
366	      res.end("Method Not Allowed");
367	      return;
368	    }
369	
370	    applyCors(res);
371	    const body = await readJsonBody(req);
372	    const parsed = callbackBodySchema.safeParse(body);
373	    if (!parsed.success) {
374	      res.writeHead(400, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });
375	      res.end(JSON.stringify({ ok: false, reason: "bad_request" }));
376	      settle(null);
377	      return;
378	    }
379	    const { token, state: returned } = parsed.data;
380	    if (returned !== state) {
381	      res.writeHead(400, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });
382	      res.end(JSON.stringify({ ok: false, reason: "state_mismatch" }));
383	      settle(null);
384	      return;
385	    }
386	    const persisted = setToken(token);
387	    res.writeHead(persisted ? 204 : 500, {
388	      "Content-Type": "application/json",
389	    });
390	    res.end(persisted ? "" : JSON.stringify({ ok: false, reason: "persist_failed" }));
391	    settle(persisted ? token : null);
392	  } catch (error) {
393	    console.error("[auth-flow] loopback handler error", error);
394	    res.writeHead(500, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
395	    res.end("Internal Server Error");
396	    settle(null);
397	  }
398	});
399	```
400	
401	And add the schema + import near the top of the file. **Consolidate the `node:http` types into the existing import** — the current file already has `import { createServer, type Server } from "node:http";`, so merge rather than adding a second line (Biome's `lint/style/useImportType` / `noUselessFragments` rules will flag split imports):
402	
403	```ts
404	import {
405	  createServer,
406	  type IncomingMessage,
407	  type Server,
408	  type ServerResponse,
409	} from "node:http";
410	import { z } from "zod";
411	
412	const callbackBodySchema = z.object({
413	  token: z.string().min(1),
414	  state: z.string().min(1),
415	});
416	```
417	
418	Delete the `responsePage()` helper and its caller-site HTML responses — the browser tab UI now lives in the web bridge.
419	
420	#### 2. `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-not-allowed)/_components/client-auth-bridge.tsx`
421	
422	**Refactor `ClientAuthBridgeProps` into a discriminated union on `mode` so POST and redirect modes are type-level exclusive.** Two-optional-callbacks with a runtime "exactly one" check is an impossible-state API; the union makes the compiler enforce it.
423	
424	```ts
425	interface ClientAuthBridgeBaseProps {
426	  fallback?: ReactNode;
427	  jwtTemplate?: string;
428	  subtitle: string;
429	  title: string;
430	}
431	
432	interface PostCallbackProps {
433	  mode: "post";
434	  buildPostCallback: (args: {
435	    searchParams: URLSearchParams;
436	  }) => { url: string; state: string } | null;
437	}
438	
439	interface RedirectProps {
440	  mode: "redirect";
441	  buildRedirectUrl: (args: {
442	    token: string;
443	    searchParams: URLSearchParams;
444	  }) => string | null;
445	}
446	
447	export type ClientAuthBridgeProps = ClientAuthBridgeBaseProps &
448	  (PostCallbackProps | RedirectProps);
449	```
450	
451	Inside the effect, branch on `props.mode`. Add **Sentry observation on web-side error paths** — without it, a prod-only CORS / preflight regression (e.g. the ALLOWED_ORIGIN env falls through to `localhost:3024` because `NODE_ENV` isn't `"production"` in a packaged build) shows as a silent "Authentication Failed" to the user with zero Sentry signal. The desktop only sees requests that reach its handler; a browser-rejected preflight never does:
452	
453	```ts
454	// Phase 3 also touches this effect — merge the one-shot-latch fix below.
455	if (props.mode === "post") {
456	  const built = props.buildPostCallback({ searchParams });
457	  if (!built) {
458	    Sentry.captureMessage("auth-bridge: buildPostCallback returned null", {
459	      level: "warning",
460	      tags: { scope: "auth-bridge.invalid_callback" },
461	    });
462	    setStatus("error");
463	    return;
464	  }
465	  let response: Response;
466	  try {
467	    response = await fetch(built.url, {
468	      method: "POST",
469	      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
470	      body: JSON.stringify({ token, state: built.state }),
471	      // No credentials — loopback doesn't accept cookies.
472	      credentials: "omit",
473	    });
474	  } catch (error) {
475	    // TypeError from fetch — browser blocked the request (CORS / PNA preflight)
476	    // or the loopback port is gone. The user sees "Authentication Failed" with
477	    // no desktop-side signal since the request never reached the handler.
478	    Sentry.captureException(error, {
479	      tags: { scope: "auth-bridge.fetch_network_error" },
480	    });
481	    setStatus("error");
482	    return;
483	  }
484	  if (!response.ok) {
485	    Sentry.captureMessage("auth-bridge: loopback POST non-ok", {
486	      level: "warning",
487	      tags: {
488	        scope: "auth-bridge.fetch_non_ok",
489	        status: String(response.status),
490	      },
491	    });
492	    setStatus("error");
493	    return;
494	  }
495	  setStatus("success");
496	  return;
497	}
498	// props.mode === "redirect" — existing path, unchanged for CLI.
499	```
500	
501	**Import style: use named imports from `@sentry/nextjs`, not `import * as Sentry`.** Existing apps/app call sites (`session-activator.tsx:4`, `oauth-button.tsx:6`) use `import { addBreadcrumb, startSpan } from "@sentry/nextjs"`. There is **no** existing `import * as Sentry` in `apps/app/src/**` — matching the named-import convention keeps the bundle tree-shakeable and tooling consistent. Rewrite the bridge snippet above accordingly:
502	
503	```ts
504	import { captureException, captureMessage } from "@sentry/nextjs";
505	// ...
506	captureMessage("auth-bridge: buildPostCallback returned null", { /* ... */ });
507	captureException(error, { tags: { scope: "auth-bridge.fetch_network_error" } });
508	```
509	
510	Desktop main (`@sentry/electron/main`) and desktop renderer (`@sentry/browser`) both already use `import * as Sentry`; keep those namespace-style to match `sentry.ts:2` and `renderer/src/main.ts:1` respectively. The inconsistency across packages is real but pre-existing — don't try to unify here.
511	
512	Extend the state union from `"loading" | "redirecting" | "error"` to `"loading" | "redirecting" | "success" | "error"` and render a "Signed in — you can close this tab" panel for `"success"`. This replaces the HTML page the loopback used to serve. The success panel may also attempt `window.close()` for better UX — note this only works if the tab was opened by JavaScript, and our tab was opened via Electron's `shell.openExternal`, so the call is a best-effort no-op in most browsers. Don't rely on it.
513	
514	#### 3. `apps/app/src/app/(app)/(user)/(pending-not-allowed)/desktop/auth/_components/desktop-auth-client.tsx`
515	
516	**Switch from `buildRedirectUrl` to `buildPostCallback`.** `validateLoopbackCallback` stays as-is (same allow-list, same URL validation).
517	
518	```tsx
519	<ClientAuthBridge
520	  mode="post"
521	  buildPostCallback={({ searchParams }) => {
522	    const state = searchParams.get("state");
523	    const callback = validateLoopbackCallback(searchParams.get("callback"));
524	    if (!(state && callback)) {
525	      return null;
526	    }
527	    // Strip any query params — POST carries token + state in the body.
528	    callback.search = "";
529	    return { url: callback.toString(), state };
530	  }}
531	  jwtTemplate="lightfast-desktop"
532	  subtitle="You'll be redirected back to the Lightfast desktop app shortly."
533	  title="Authenticating…"
534	/>
535	```
536	
537	#### 4. CLI flow — explicit `mode="redirect"`
538	
539	`cli-auth-client.tsx` continues to use `buildRedirectUrl`, but must now pass `mode="redirect"` for the union to discriminate. Leave a short comment referencing the follow-up tracking item so a future reader sees the parity gap is intentional, not an oversight.
540	
541	#### 5. `apps/desktop/src/main/auth-flow.ts` — serialize concurrent `beginSignIn` calls
542	
543	Today each call spawns a fresh loopback server on a new port, opens a new browser tab, and uses a fresh 256-bit state nonce. Two rapid clicks on "Sign In" produce two of everything — first to complete wins, second times out at 5 min. Confusing, and halfway to a resource leak.
544	
545	Guard with a module-scope in-flight promise:
546	
547	```ts
548	let inflight: Promise<string | null> | null = null;
549	
550	export async function beginSignIn(): Promise<string | null> {
551	  if (inflight) {
552	    return inflight;
553	  }
554	  inflight = (async () => {
555	    try {
556	      // ... existing beginSignIn body, now wrapped ...
557	    } finally {
558	      inflight = null;
559	    }
560	  })();
561	  return inflight;
562	}
563	```
564	
565	All concurrent callers receive the same promise; the `finally` clears the slot on settle, timeout, or error so the next sign-in attempt starts fresh.
566	
567	**Implementation note**: the existing `beginSignIn` body returns a `new Promise<string | null>((resolve) => { /* server setup */ })`. When wrapping inside the async IIFE, `return` that promise so the outer `async` awaits it:
568	
569	```ts
570	inflight = (async () => {
571	  try {
572	    return await new Promise<string | null>((resolve) => {
573	      // ... existing server setup, settle() calls resolve() ...
574	    });
575	  } finally {
576	    inflight = null;
577	  }
578	})();
579	```
580	
581	Without the explicit `return await`, the IIFE resolves immediately with `undefined` and `finally` clears `inflight` before the server ever settles — every concurrent call starts its own flow anyway.
582	
583	#### 6. Renderer — failure toast + window focus on sign-in
584	
585	Two small renderer-side behaviors wired to the sign-in promise chain:
586	
587	1. **Failure toast**: the only caller is `apps/desktop/src/renderer/src/react/app-shell.tsx:38` (`onSignIn={() => void window.lightfastBridge.auth.signIn()}`), fire-and-forget today. Replace the `void` with a `.then`: when `beginSignIn()` resolves `null` (any non-success path — timeout, state mismatch, bad body, 400 response, closed tab), show `toast.error("Sign-in didn't complete — please try again")`. Generic wording covers all null cases; "timed out" would be misleading for e.g. state-mismatch returns. Success (non-null) needs no renderer-side action — the auth-state emit already drives the shell swap.
588	2. **Window focus on sign-in success**: the auth-state subscriber at `apps/desktop/src/main/index.ts:367-371` (the `onAuthChanged` callback that loops `BrowserWindow.getAllWindows()` and `webContents.send`s the snapshot) should additionally call `win.show()` + `win.focus()` on transitions from signed-out → signed-in. Track the previous `isSignedIn` in a module-scope variable; only fire focus when the flag flips from `false` to `true`. This brings the desktop to the front the moment the bridge POSTs, matching the UX of `gh auth login` / `gcloud auth login` surfacing their terminal.
589	
590	Gate on **transition only** (false → true). Token refreshes that keep `isSignedIn: true` must not yank focus.
591	
592	**Initialize `prev` from the actual boot-time auth state, not `false`.** `load()` is called during boot and populates the in-memory token but does **not** fire `emit()`. So:
593	- If the user boots signed-in, no emit happens — `createWindow()` at `windows/factory.ts` attaches `win.once("ready-to-show", () => win.show())`, so the window will surface itself naturally once Electron is ready. No post-boot focus-yank needed.
594	- If a token refresh happens later in that session, it emits `true`. If `prev` was initialized to `false` (the JS default), that looks like a `false → true` transition and we'd incorrectly yank focus.
595	
596	The fix: when the subscriber is wired in `index.ts:367`, read the current snapshot (`Boolean(getSnapshot().isSignedIn)` or however the auth-store exposes it) and seed `prev` with that value. The module-scope state becomes:
597	
598	```ts
599	let prev = Boolean(getSnapshot().isSignedIn); // accurate at subscriber-attach time
600	
601	onAuthChanged((snapshot) => {
602	  for (const win of BrowserWindow.getAllWindows()) {
603	    win.webContents.send(IpcChannels.authChanged, snapshot);
604	  }
605	  const next = Boolean(snapshot.isSignedIn);
606	  if (!prev && next) {
607	    for (const win of BrowserWindow.getAllWindows()) {
608	      win.show();
609	      win.focus();
610	    }
611	  }
612	  prev = next;
613	});
614	```
615	
616	This way:
617	- Boot signed-out → first user sign-in → emit(true) → `prev=false, next=true` → focus. ✓
618	- Boot signed-in + token refresh → emit(true) → `prev=true, next=true` → no focus. ✓
619	- Sign-out mid-session → emit(false) → `prev=true, next=false` → no focus (gate doesn't match). ✓
620	- Re-sign-in after sign-out → emit(true) → `prev=false, next=true` → focus. ✓
621	
622	No separate "skip first emit" sentinel is needed — the bug was in the default value of `prev`, not in the transition detection.
623	
624	#### 7. Observability — Sentry at auth-flow error sites
625	
626	Use `Sentry.captureException` for real errors and `Sentry.captureMessage(msg, { level: "warning" })` for anomalies that don't throw. **Do not use `addBreadcrumb` standalone here** — breadcrumbs only attach to a subsequent `captureException` in the same scope, so a timeout that doesn't throw produces zero Sentry events and disappears.
627	
628	Real failures (`captureException`, with `tags.scope`):
629	
630	- `startLoopbackServer()` bind failure → `scope: "auth-flow.bind"`
631	- `setToken(token) === false` after a successful browser POST → `scope: "auth-flow.persist_failed"` — user completed the browser flow but desktop couldn't save
632	- Outer handler catch (the `try/catch` around the request handler) → `scope: "auth-flow.handler_error"`
633	
634	Anomalies (`captureMessage` at `level: "warning"`, with `tags.scope`):
635	
636	- State mismatch in POST handler → `"auth-flow: state mismatch"`, `scope: "auth-flow.state_mismatch"`
637	- Forbidden origin in POST handler → `"auth-flow: forbidden origin"`, `scope: "auth-flow.forbidden_origin"` — worth tracking as a signal of a misconfigured prod origin or a local probe
638	- Timeout settle (the 5-minute no-callback path) → `"auth-flow: sign-in timeout"`, `scope: "auth-flow.timeout"`
639	
640	These are the signals that distinguish "silent prod regression" from "we can see it happened and why". `captureMessage` creates a real Sentry event at warning level so anomaly paths are visible in the dashboard even when nothing throws.
641	
642	### Residual risk — what fetch-POST does and does not cover
643	
644	Honest framing of the threat model for future readers:
645	
646	| Surface | GET redirect (today) | fetch-POST (this phase) | PKCE code exchange (rejected) |
647	| --- | --- | --- | --- |
648	| Browser URL bar | JWT visible | Clean | Clean |
649	| Browser history | JWT persisted | Clean | Clean |
650	| `Referer` headers to third parties | JWT leaks | Clean | Clean |
651	| URL-logging browser extensions | JWT captured | Clean | Clean |
652	| Request-body-capable extensions (`webRequest` + body perms) | JWT captured | JWT captured | Clean |
653	| DevTools Network tab (open by user) | JWT visible | JWT visible | Clean (opaque code) |
654	| In-memory fetch request body | N/A | Present briefly | Clean (code not JWT) |
655	
656	fetch-POST clears every URL-surface leak, which is the bar CodeRabbit #7 asked us to meet. It does **not** make the JWT invisible to a user who already installed a request-body-reading extension, nor to DevTools. PKCE would close those gaps by replacing the JWT with a single-use code that's redeemed for a JWT over a server-to-server exchange — but that requires a new `/api/desktop/auth/exchange` endpoint and a Redis-backed code↔JWT map. Rejected as scope creep for a 24h-bounded localhost handoff. If the threat model ever expands (e.g., longer-lived tokens, shared machines), revisit PKCE.
657	
658	### Success Criteria
659	
660	#### Automated Verification:
661	
662	- [ ] `pnpm --filter @lightfast/desktop typecheck` passes.
663	- [ ] `pnpm --filter @lightfast/app typecheck` passes.
664	- [ ] `pnpm biome check apps/desktop/src/main/auth-flow.ts apps/app/src/app/\\(app\\)/\\(user\\)/\\(pending-not-allowed\\)/_components/client-auth-bridge.tsx apps/app/src/app/\\(app\\)/\\(user\\)/\\(pending-not-allowed\\)/desktop/auth/_components/desktop-auth-client.tsx` is clean.
665	- [ ] `pnpm --filter @api/app vitest run` still passes (no behavioral changes to `resolveClerkSession`).
666	
667	#### Manual Verification:
668	
669	- [ ] `pnpm dev:desktop-stack` + `pnpm dev:desktop` boot cleanly.
670	- [ ] Click "Sign in with Lightfast" → default browser opens at `localhost:3024/desktop/auth?state=…&callback=http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback`. Complete Clerk sign-in.
671	- [ ] After the bridge flips to "Signed in — close this tab", open browser DevTools → History. Confirm **no entry contains `token=`** in the URL. Only `state` and `callback` should appear.
672	- [ ] Open DevTools → Network. Confirm the handoff is a `POST http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback` returning 204, with JWT present only in the request body.
673	- [ ] Craft a malicious `callback` param (`https://evil.com/callback`) → bridge renders "Authentication Failed"; no POST is fired.
674	- [ ] Mismatched `state` (mutate in-flight via DevTools) → loopback returns 400 with `state_mismatch`; desktop remains on auth-gate.
675	- [ ] `NODE_ENV` sanity in packaged builds: `getApiOrigin()` falls through to `http://localhost:3024` when `NODE_ENV !== "production"`. Packaged Electron apps don't always have `NODE_ENV` set in `process.env` (depends on electron-builder / Squirrel config). Add a one-liner `console.log("[auth-flow] ALLOWED_ORIGIN =", ALLOWED_ORIGIN);` at module load, build a signed dev DMG, launch it, and confirm the logged origin matches the expected prod value (`https://lightfast.ai`) — not `http://localhost:3024`. If it falls through to localhost, production sign-in will 403 on origin. This is a **pre-existing** concern (the helper predates this plan) but Phase 2 makes it load-bearing for CORS.
676	- [ ] Origin check: `curl -X POST -H "Origin: http://evil.com" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"token":"x","state":"x"}' http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback` returns 403. (Port is printed in the desktop console log.)
677	- [ ] Empty-Origin rejection: `curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"token":"x","state":"x"}' http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback` (no Origin header) also returns 403 — confirms the tightened origin check.
678	- [ ] PNA header: `curl -i -X OPTIONS -H "Origin: https://lightfast.ai" -H "Access-Control-Request-Method: POST" -H "Access-Control-Request-Private-Network: true" http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback` returns `Access-Control-Allow-Private-Network: true` in the response headers.
679	- [ ] Double-handshake guard (StrictMode): with `apps/app` running in dev (StrictMode on by default in Next.js 15), complete a sign-in. The Network tab should show **exactly one** POST to `http://127.0.0.1:<port>/callback`, not two. Confirms the `didStart` latch bars React's second effect invocation.
680	- [ ] Concurrent sign-in serialization: click "Sign In" twice in rapid succession (< 500ms apart). Expect **one** browser tab to open (not two), **one** loopback port to be logged, and a clean sign-in on completion. The second IPC call should resolve to the same token as the first.
681	- [ ] Sign-in timeout UX: click "Sign In", close the browser tab without completing. After ~5 minutes, the desktop should display a toast ("Sign-in didn't complete — please try again") and return to the pre-sign-in state. Sentry should show an `auth-flow.timeout` warning-level event (from `captureMessage`, not a breadcrumb).
682	- [ ] Window focus on sign-in: from a desktop window that's been command-tab'd away (not focused), complete a sign-in in the browser. The desktop window should auto-`show()` + `focus()` the moment the POST resolves.
683	- [ ] Window focus does not fire on refresh: while signed in, trigger a token refresh (or simulate an `emit({ isSignedIn: true })` on an already-signed-in state). The desktop window should **not** steal focus. Confirms the focus call is gated on the signed-out→signed-in transition.
684	- [ ] Regression: sign-in via `apps/app` browser-cookie flow still works (`/sign-in` unchanged).
685	- [ ] Regression: CLI flow at `/cli/auth` still completes (smoke test — not shipping changes there, just ensuring `ClientAuthBridge` refactor didn't break it).
686	
687	**Implementation Note**: Pause for human confirmation after Phase 2. The browser-history test is the defining acceptance criterion for #7 — don't proceed to Phase 3 until that has been eyeballed on a real Clerk dev session.
688	
689	---
